Issues.Body:
Currently when we're analyzing an object literal that is passed into an Angular decorator, we only look for property assignments, which covers most cases, but breaks down if something is defined as a method declaration, e.g.

```ts
@Injectable({
  // Won't be picked up
  useFactory() {
    return new Service();
  }
})
class Service {}
```

These changes make it so that we pick up method declarations too.

In the process of working on this issue, I found another one: we were generating invalid code when emitting a call to a `FunctionExpression`. The problem was that we'd create a `CallExpression` directly from the `FunctionExpression` which would result an expression like `function foo() {}()`. I've added some code so that we wrap the function in parentheses: `(function foo() {})()`.

Fixes #38578.

**Note:** I didn't add any equivalent tests for the runtime, because the runtime tests are in JIT mode which doesn't have the problem.

# 🚀 feature request

### Relevant Package
@angular/router


### Description

I would like to propose a feature to router, that would add names to route levels, and allow to render multiple components from one router outlet like this


### Proposed usage overview
[blade layout example below explained](https://ibb.co/mT00tw4)

```typescript
{ path: 'invoices', component: InvoicesBladeContainer, levelName: 'invoices', children: [
   { path: '', component: InvoicesList, children: [
      { path: 'details', component: InvoiceDetails, level: 'invoices', children: [
         { path: 'lines', component: InvoiceLinesList, children: [
           { path: 'create', component: InvoiceLineCreate, level: 'invoices'  } 
          ] }      
      ] }       
  ] }
], }
```

so we get ability to render components next to each other instead of always one into another. And thus blade layout. 

This is of course very naive implementation. I already can see problem with how injector should handle that - should it be by like routes go or component outlets - this will probably be easier. 

### router outlet template
One more thing that would go well with this proposition it possibility to provide an template to router-outlet that would wrap each child
```html
<router-outlet template="wrapper"></router-outlet>
<ng-template #wrapper>
    <div class="blade"><ng-content></div>
</ng-template>
```

or 
```typescript
{ path: 'invoices', component: InvoicesBladeContainer, levelName: 'invoices', wrapperComponent: BladeWrapper,  children: [
], }
```
here wrapperComponent would be rendered as a wrapper for each child of this router outlet, and not rendered at all of no children would exists, for example when exact route would be hit.

When using CommonJs as module format TypeScript will generate unreferenced `require` when using `ts.createImportDeclaration`.

```js
const external_component_html_1 = require("!raw-loader!./external.component.html");
const core_1 = require("@angular/core");
let ExampleComponent = class ExampleComponent {
};
ExampleComponent = __decorate([
    core_1.Component({
        selector: 'example-compoent',
        template: __NG_CLI_RESOURCE__0,
    })
], ExampleComponent);
```

More context: https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/18369#issuecomment-329852888

Closes #18718

# 🐞 Bug report

### Command
- [x] serve

### Is this a regression?

Yes, I think it's a regression.


### Description

If you first create a component without importing the necessary modules, and then add these necessary modules, the component is not updated until you change the component itself.

Not sure if this bug is Angular CLI, maybe it's more of an Angular Material bug.

## 🔬 Minimal Reproduction

**Step 1**
```bash
ng new my-project
cd my-project
ng add @angular/material
```
**Step 2**
In `src/app/app.module.ts` import only `ReactiveFormsModule` and `MatFormFieldModule`:
```ts
import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { ReactiveFormsModule } from '@angular/forms';
import { MatFormFieldModule } from '@angular/material/form-field';

import { AppComponent } from './app.component';
import { BrowserAnimationsModule } from '@angular/platform-browser/animations';

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    AppComponent
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule,
    BrowserAnimationsModule,
    ReactiveFormsModule,
    MatFormFieldModule,
  ],
  providers: [],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent]
})
export class AppModule { }
```

**Step 3**
Put this code to `src/app/app.component.html`:
```html
<mat-form-field>
  <input matInput>
</mat-form-field>
```

**Step 4**
```bash
ng serve
```

In console the browser see:
```text
ERROR Error: mat-form-field must contain a MatFormFieldControl.
```

**Step 5**
Import `MatInputModule`:
```ts
import { MatInputModule } from '@angular/material/input';
// ...
imports: [
//..
  MatInputModule
]
```

In the browser still:
```text
ERROR Error: mat-form-field must contain a MatFormFieldControl.
```

**Step 6**

Make any change in `src/app/app.component.ts` and the error disappear.


